<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-11-21T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-11-21T16:00:00-05:00" n="488" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d488">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 E. W. 1939/26011a:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-11-21T17:00:00-04:00">November
                                    21, 1942—5 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>303. The Department would be interested in a summary of the reaction in
                            Liberia to the events which have taken place in North Africa.<note n="42" xml:id="d488fn42">Invasion by American forces beginning
                                November 8, 1942; for correspondence, see <ref target="frus1942v02#pg_429">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                                    pp. 429</ref> ff.</note> Has there been any change in the
                            attitude of Liberian officials toward the need of protection by United
                            States defense forces?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>